  "doc_id": "43851",
  "text": "All the available samples, both labeled and unlabeled, are arranged into a matrix, X 2 R mÂN , each of whose columns represents the feature vector of a sample. To achieve a robust classifier, we seek to denoise this matrix. Following [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] , this could be done by assuming that X can be spanned on a low-rank subspace and therefore should be rank-deficient. This assumption supports the fact that samples from same classes are more correlated [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] and linearly-dependent. Accordingly, the original matrix X is decomposed into the summation of two counterparts, D 2 R mÂN and E 2 R mÂN . The former represents the denoised data matrix, while the latter is the error matrix. This is similar to RPCA [CITATION_5] , used in many computer vision applications. With this decomposition, we can assume that the denoised data matrix shall be rankdeficient and the error matrix sparse.",
